  "doc_id": "29926",
  "text": "It has been reported before that somatotropes can transdifferentiate to thyrotropes after thyroidectomy [CITATION_1] or protracted hypothyroidism [CITATION_2] . Cells containing both hormones, GH and TSH, were observed during this process [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . We find here that thyrosomatotropes are already present in the AP of normal mice, especially in females, but other hormonal combinations, for example thyrogonadotropes, were much more frequent. This suggests that the appearance of bihormonal cells is not aimless. Somatotropes are much more frequent than gonadotropes in mice pituitary [CITATION_5] , and, at random, the combination TSH-GH should be much more likely. On the other hand, thyrosomatotrope formation should be specifically favored by the pressure of low plasma thyroid hormone levels in hypothyroidism. As with other polyhormonal cells [CITATION_6] , polyhormonal thyrotropes were more frequent in females than in males, suggesting that the sexual cycle may favor transdifferentiation. It is remarkable that sex differences did not affect gonadotropins (LH) or PRL, which were similarly costored with TRH in males and females. However, costorage of ACTH and GH by thyrotropes was affected by sex (Fig. 2) .",
